total_CO2<- gapminder %>% 
  group_by(iso3, time) %>% 
  filter(co2 != "NA", name != "NA") %>% 
  summarise(avgCO2 = mean(co2)) %>% 
  filter(iso3 == "USA" | iso3 == "CHN" | iso3 == "IND" | iso3 == "VNM" | iso3 == "KOR")
  
 

total_CO2 %>% 
  ggplot(aes(time, avgCO2, col = factor(iso3))) +
  geom_line() +
  labs(x = "Time (yr)", y = "Average CO2 Emmission (kt)", col = "Countries",
       title = "Average CO2 Emission Over Year")

The graph suggests that out of the 5 countries chosen, China on average emits the highest amount of Co2 after around 2005. China has the greatest positive trend throughout the years with a spike in emissions after year 2000. The US started with the greatest amount of average co2 emission but has not had any major spikes, and is number 2 after 2000. While India, Korea, and Vietnam emits the least amount of Co2 throughout the years in this group.

percapita <- gapminder %>%
  group_by(iso3, time) %>% 
  filter(co2_PC != "NA", name != "NA") %>%
  summarise(avgcapita = mean(co2_PC)) %>% 
  filter(iso3 == "USA" | iso3 == "CHN" | iso3 == "IND" | iso3 == "VNM" | iso3 == "KOR")


percapita %>%
  ggplot(aes(time, avgcapita, col = factor(iso3))) +
  geom_line() +
  labs(x = "Time (yr)", y = "Average CO2 Emmission Per Capita (kt)", col = "Countries", 
       title = "Average CO2 Emission CP Over Year")

The graph suggests that the USA has the greatest average Co2 emission per-capita from 1960 to 2019, however there is a steady negative trend with the US releasing less CO2 per-capita in 2019 than compared to previous years. With the other countries, there is a positive trend where they have been increasing CO2 emissions per-capital.

Part 4 - GDP Per Capita

gapminder %>% 
  group_by(name) %>% 
  select(region, time, GDP_PC, lifeExpectancy, totalPopulation) %>% 
  filter(time == 1960) %>% 
  filter(GDP_PC != "NA", lifeExpectancy != "NA", name != "NA", totalPopulation != "NA") %>% 
  ggplot() +
  geom_point(aes(lifeExpectancy, GDP_PC, color = region, size = totalPopulation)) +
  labs(title = "1960 GDP PerCap. vs Life Expectancy", x = "Life Expectancy (Yr)", 
       y = "GDP Per Capita (Constant 2010 US$)", color ="Continent", size = "Country \n Size")

The scatter plot suggests that as life expectancy increases in years, so does the GDP Per Capita. Additionally, the plot depicts where continents are on the scale. For instance, we can see that Africa is towards the left end with lower life expectancy and lower GDP CP while Europe is on the right side of the plot with higher life expectancy and higher GDP CP. It also specifies how large a country is by the size of the dot. Larger dot indicates a larger country and smaller dot indicates a smaller country.

gapminder %>% 
  group_by(name) %>% 
  select(region, time, GDP_PC, lifeExpectancy, totalPopulation) %>% 
  filter(time == 2019) %>% 
  filter(GDP_PC != "NA", lifeExpectancy != "NA", name != "NA", totalPopulation != "NA") %>% 
  ggplot() +

  labs(title = "2019 GDP PerCap. vs Life Expectancy", x = "Life Expectancy (Yr)", 
       y = "GDP Per Capita (Constant 2010 US$)", color ="Continent", size = "Country \n Size")

The scatter plot suggests that countries across diffferent continents have closer in life expectancy. However theres is still a gap in GDP per capita depending on the Continent.
